<quantity box="[1063,1194,1993,2017]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7" metricValueMax="3.9" metricValueMin="3.5" pageId="26" pageNumber="143" unit="mm" value="3.7" valueMax="3.9" valueMin="3.5">3.5–3.9 mm</quantity>
. Coloration (
<figureCitation box="[1352,1432,1993,2017]" captionStart="Figs 1–41" captionStartId="45.[151,191,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[152,1389,232,1855]" captionTargetId="figure-203@45.[151,1398,232,1874]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figs 1–41:Antennae of Zyrasspp.:kraatzi(1),exasperatus(2),pindarae (3–5),perforatus(6),championi(7),pallipes (8),condignus (9), nitens (10), truncatus (11), nilgiriensis (12), hirsutiventris (13), russiceps (14), brignolii (15), hastatus (16), parageminus (17–18), latilobatus (19), alternans (20), hirtus (21), nigroaeneus (22), luteipes (23), longilobatus (24), morvani (25), gratellus (Malaysia) (26), castaneus, lectotype (27),proximus (28–29),novinversus (30–31), brevilobatus(32), parvicollis(33), ambulans (34),matangensis (35), densissimus (36), densihirtus (37), nigrihirtus (38), gratellus (Sulawesi) (39), gardneri (40), titan (41). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742367/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="143">Figs 40</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[831,859,2025,2049]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="143">62</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[870,900,2025,2049]" captionStart="Figs 82–99" captionStartId="53.[151,191,2018,2040]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-116@53.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="Figs 82–99: Abdomen of Zyras spp.: pindarae (82–85), perforatus (86), championi (87), pallipes (88), longilobatus (89), hastatus (90), truncatus (91), latilobatus (92), morvani (93), condignus (94), hirtus (95), gardneri (96), hirsutiventris (97), parageminus (98), alternans (99). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742383/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="143">96</figureCitation>
): head black; pronotum brown to blackish-brown; elytra reddish to reddish-brown, with the postero-lateral portions diffusely darker; abdomen more or less distinctly bicoloured; tergites II–IV reddish to dark-brown, V–VII (except for the anterior margin of V) dark-brown to blackish, and VIII brown to dark-brown; legs yellowish; antennae bicoloured, blackish-brown with antennomeres IX–XI yellowish; maxillary palpi dark-brown with palpomere IV yellowish to yellowish-brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,756,233,2017]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[232,307,457,481]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Fig. 62</figureCitation>
) distinctly transverse, median portion extensively impunctate; punctures in lateral portions moderately sparse and moderately coarse. Eyes much longer than postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[159,234,585,609]" captionStart="Figs 1–41" captionStartId="45.[151,191,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[152,1389,232,1855]" captionTargetId="figure-203@45.[151,1398,232,1874]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figs 1–41:Antennae of Zyrasspp.:kraatzi(1),exasperatus(2),pindarae (3–5),perforatus(6),championi(7),pallipes (8),condignus (9), nitens (10), truncatus (11), nilgiriensis (12), hirsutiventris (13), russiceps (14), brignolii (15), hastatus (16), parageminus (17–18), latilobatus (19), alternans (20), hirtus (21), nigroaeneus (22), luteipes (23), longilobatus (24), morvani (25), gratellus (Malaysia) (26), castaneus, lectotype (27),proximus (28–29),novinversus (30–31), brevilobatus(32), parvicollis(33), ambulans (34),matangensis (35), densissimus (36), densihirtus (37), nigrihirtus (38), gratellus (Sulawesi) (39), gardneri (40), titan (41). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742367/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
) 2.7–3.0 mm long and rather slender; antennomeres IV–VI oblong, VII approximately as long as broad, VIII–X weakly transverse, X much less than 1.5 times as broad as long, and XI short, shorter than the combined length of IX and X.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,756,233,2017]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[273,347,745,769]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Fig. 62</figureCitation>
) moderately transverse, approximately 1.15 times as broad as long and approximately 1.3 times as broad as head, broadest in anterior half; punctation rather fine and moderately dense, almost regularly distributed; midline narrowly impunctate; anterior margin and anterior half of lateral margins with numerous long brown setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,756,233,2017]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[236,311,969,993]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Fig. 62</figureCitation>
) 0.85–0.90 times as long as pronotum; punctation moderately coarse, very dense, and defined, regularly distributed; whole disc with dense and sub-erect brown pubescence. Hind wings fully developed. Metatarsomere I approximately as long as, or shorter than, the combined length of II–IV.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,756,233,2017]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">
Abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[271,345,1161,1185]" captionStart="Figs 82–99" captionStartId="53.[151,191,2018,2040]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-116@53.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="Figs 82–99: Abdomen of Zyras spp.: pindarae (82–85), perforatus (86), championi (87), pallipes (88), longilobatus (89), hastatus (90), truncatus (91), latilobatus (92), morvani (93), condignus (94), hirtus (95), gardneri (96), hirsutiventris (97), parageminus (98), alternans (99). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742383/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Fig. 96</figureCitation>
) approximately as broad as elytra, with moderately deep anterior impressions on tergites III–V; anterior impressions of tergites III–V each with a transverse row of moderately coarse non-setiferous punctures; tergites III–V with sparse micropunctation on disc, with a lateral setiferous puncture on either side, and with several setiferous punctures at posterior margins; tergite VI with extensive non-setiferous punctures in anterior half to anterior three-fourths, with micropunctation in posterior portion with some lateral setiferous punctures and with several setiferous punctures at posterior margin; tergite VII with more or less extensive non-setiferous punctation in anterior half and with moderately sparse setiferous punctation not arranged in distinct rows in posterior half, posterior margin with palisade fringe; tergite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[159,246,1641,1665]" captionStart="Figs 174–190" captionStartId="58.[189,229,2020,2042]" captionTargetBox="[190,1430,246,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-107@58.[189,1436,237,1976]" captionText="Figs 174–190: Zyras gardneri (174–177), Z. hirsutiventris (178–181), Z. luteipes (182–186), and Z. russiceps (187–190): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (174–175, 178–179, 182–183, 187–188); male tergite VIII (176, 180, 185, 189); male sternite VIII (177, 181, 186, 190); paramere (184). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888372" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888372/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Fig. 176</figureCitation>
) with rather dense and long brown setae in posterior third, posterior margin shallowly concave in the middle; all sternites with long brown pubescence posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,756,233,2017]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">
♂: posterior margin of sternite VIII strongly convex (
<figureCitation box="[159,247,1801,1825]" captionStart="Figs 174–190" captionStartId="58.[189,229,2020,2042]" captionTargetBox="[190,1430,246,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-107@58.[189,1436,237,1976]" captionText="Figs 174–190: Zyras gardneri (174–177), Z. hirsutiventris (178–181), Z. luteipes (182–186), and Z. russiceps (187–190): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (174–175, 178–179, 182–183, 187–188); male tergite VIII (176, 180, 185, 189); male sternite VIII (177, 181, 186, 190); paramere (184). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888372" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888372/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Fig. 177</figureCitation>
); median lobe of aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[604,748,1801,1825]" captionStart="Figs 174–190" captionStartId="58.[189,229,2020,2042]" captionTargetBox="[190,1430,246,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-107@58.[189,1436,237,1976]" captionText="Figs 174–190: Zyras gardneri (174–177), Z. hirsutiventris (178–181), Z. luteipes (182–186), and Z. russiceps (187–190): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (174–175, 178–179, 182–183, 187–188); male tergite VIII (176, 180, 185, 189); male sternite VIII (177, 181, 186, 190); paramere (184). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888372" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888372/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Figs 174–175</figureCitation>
) approximately 
<quantity box="[314,396,1833,1857]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="27" pageNumber="144" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.1 mm</quantity>
long; ventral process somewhat constricted basally in ventral view; crista apicalis small; paramere approximately 
<quantity box="[430,524,1897,1921]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.05" pageId="27" pageNumber="144" unit="mm" value="1.05">1.05 mm</quantity>
long and with very short apical lobe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[151,756,233,2017]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">♀: posterior margin of sternite VIII weakly concave in the middle.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[794,1399,233,513]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[794,1007,233,257]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: As can be inferred from external (dense and long pubescence on the forebody and on the abdominal sternites; broad pronotum; rather large body size), as well as from the male sexual characters (apical lobe of paramere very short), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1939" box="[1193,1309,361,385]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gardneri">
<emphasis box="[1193,1309,361,385]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Z. gardneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="KRAATZ" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[865,955,393,417]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="27" pageNumber="144" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirtus">
<emphasis box="[865,955,393,417]" italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Z. hirtus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. Among the species of this group, it is characterized by the coloration (particularly of the antennae), the punctation pattern of the abdomen, and by the morphology of the median lobe of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="144" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="27.[794,1399,553,673]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[794,1157,553,577]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Distribution and natural history</emphasis>
: The known distribution is confined to several localities in 
<collectingCountry box="[1214,1277,585,609]" name="Nepal" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Nepal</collectingCountry>
and North 
<collectingCountry box="[794,850,617,641]" name="India" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">India</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[867,939,617,641]" captionStart="Map 7" captionStartId="67.[151,196,1246,1267]" captionTargetBox="[351,1198,232,1238]" captionTargetId="figure-79@67.[351,1198,232,1238]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="Map 7: Revised distributions of Zyras gardneri (black circles), Z. hirsutiventris (white diamonds), Z. parageminus (black triangles), Z. hastatus (white triangle), Z. hirtus (white circles), and Z. latilobatus (star) in India and adjacent regions." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742413" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742413/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Map 7</figureCitation>
). The altitudes range from approximately 
<quantity box="[794,947,649,673]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="0.8" pageId="27" pageNumber="144" unit="m" value="1300.0" valueMax="1800.0" valueMin="800.0">800 to 1800 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
